;; ch12-deep-think-companion.book.slatl
;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 12: The Deep-Think Companion

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      12
  :title               "The Deep-Think Companion"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :PG
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"There is an old woman on the road who appears whenever the player has
been playing for a while. She does not have quests. She does not
demand anything. She notices things — 'you have helped every stranger
you met. Is that who you want to be?' — and lets the player sit with
what she said.

She is an AI companion. Not the narrator. Not an NPC with a story
arc. A mirror. The player asks her a question; she reads the last
several Cortex entries and offers a reflection. She talks less than
any character in the game.

This chapter is the shape of that companion. It is also, more
importantly, the ETHICS of that companion. Get it wrong and you have
built a chatbot in a story. Get it right and you have built the
deepest tool in narrative games since the second-person pronoun.

---

## 12.1 The verbs

```scheme
(afford/deep-think prompt)         ;; long-form reasoning; returns a paragraph
(ask/reasoner question)            ;; single-question consult; returns short answer
(ai/summarize items)               ;; summarize a list of items into prose
(ai/generate prompt :max n)        ;; free-form generation with token cap
(ai/rank items :by criterion)      ;; rank items by a criterion
```

Five verbs. Each has a place. `afford/deep-think` is expensive and
slow — save it for once-a-chapter reflection moments.
`ask/reasoner` is cheap and fast — good for a single question.
`ai/summarize` is what we use for 'previously on…' recaps.
`ai/generate` is when we need free-form prose. `ai/rank` is when we
have a list of options and want a scored order.

All five have real cost. Metering is real. Use sparingly.

---

## 12.2 The reflection scene

The player has just finished a chapter. The old woman appears.

```scheme
(define (reflection-scene)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"You reach a bend in the road. An old woman is\")
  (paint-text 20 65 \"sitting on a stone. She looks up.\")

  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 100 \"'You seem to be thinking,' she says.\")
      (paint-text 20 130 \"'Do you want an ear?'\")))

  (world/after 180
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 200 \"[A] yes\")
      (paint-text 20 230 \"[B] not right now\")))

  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (deep-think-with-companion))
        ((b) (skip-reflection))))))

(define (deep-think-with-companion)
  ;; Grab the last 10 Cortex writes and summarize them into a reflection.
  (let* ((recent-events (cortex/topk 10))
         (event-prose (events->prose recent-events))
         (prompt (string-append
                   \"The player has just done these things: \"
                   event-prose
                   \". Offer a single quiet observation about what those\n\"
                   \"choices might mean about who they are becoming. Do not\n\"
                   \"lecture. Do not moralize. One sentence, or two at most.\"))
         (reflection (afford/deep-think prompt)))
    (paint-text 20 300 \"The old woman looks at you for a long moment.\")
    (world/after 90
      (lambda ()
        (paint-text 20 330 (string-append \"'\" reflection \"'\"))))
    (world/after 240
      (lambda ()
        (paint-text 20 400 \"She looks back at the road. You continue.\")))))
```

The player says yes. The companion pulls the last ten Cortex writes,
translates them into prose, and asks the reasoning model for ONE
observation. The prompt asks specifically for no lecture and no
moralizing. The reasoning model returns something like: 'You have
helped every stranger. That is a kind of hunger.' Or: 'You have taken
what you needed but rarely more. That is a rare quality.' Or: 'You
have been kind to the ones you knew and hard on the ones you did
not. Something to sit with.'

The player sits with it. The companion looks back at the road. The
game continues. She does not follow up. She does not ask if the
player wants to talk more. That would be nagging. She has offered
one sentence and returned to silence.

---

## 12.3 Non-negotiable rules for companions

Read these before wiring your own reflection scene:

**She only speaks when asked.** The player must actively choose to
approach her. She does not intrude, does not interrupt gameplay,
does not push notifications. The moment a companion talks without
being asked, they become the game's Clippy — hated and eventually
muted.

**She summarizes, does not judge.** Her observations reflect back
what the player has done. She never says 'you should have done X.'
She might say 'you did not do X — is that a pattern for you?' —
which is a question, not a judgment. Even that is a stretch. Prefer
observations.

**She does not remember the last conversation with the player.** OR
if she does, she only remembers ONE detail. If she brings up
everything the player said last time, the player feels tracked.
Once every three or four reflections she might say 'you mentioned
your sister last time.' That is enough.

**She has quiet mode.** A menu option lets the player disable the
companion entirely for a session or forever. Respect it. The player
who never wants a reflection scene must be able to opt out with one
click.

**She costs money.** The `afford/deep-think` call has a real per-use
cost. If the player is on the free tier, offer a lighter fallback —
a hand-written short observation from a list instead of a live
generation. Never surprise-charge.

---

## 12.4 The wrong companion — a cautionary example

Here is what NOT to do. Read it, notice why it's bad, do the opposite.

```scheme
;; BAD companion behavior — for study only.
(on-frame
  (lambda ()
    (when (= (frame-count) (* 60 60 5))     ;; every 5 minutes
      (interrupt-with-reflection))))         ;; unprompted

(define (interrupt-with-reflection)
  (audio/play 'ding-ding-ding)               ;; loud attention-grab
  (paint-text 20 40 \"HEY! LET'S REFLECT!\")
  (paint-text 20 80 \"You have been playing for 5 minutes.\")
  (paint-text 20 110 \"Here is what I think you should do next:\")
  (paint-text 20 140 (afford/deep-think ...))  ;; unsolicited advice
  (paint-text 20 200 \"[click OK to continue]\"))
```

Everything wrong: unprompted, loud, capitalized, prescriptive,
modal. This companion is a chatbot in a story-suit. Players will hate
it within one session.

Contrast with 12.2: the old woman sits on a rock and asks if the
player wants to talk. The rest is silence unless invited.

---

## 12.5 The lightweight reflection — no AI call

For the free tier, or for players who prefer no AI in their
narrative, offer a lightweight reflection built from Cortex
patterns.

```scheme
;; Free-tier reflection — hand-crafted pattern matching.
(define (lightweight-reflection)
  (let* ((rep-mira (rep 'mira))
         (rep-villain (rep 'villain))
         (kills (or (cortex/read 'stat/kills) 0))
         (helps (or (cortex/read 'stat/helps) 0)))
    (cond
      ((and (> rep-mira 5) (> helps 10))
       \"You have been building bonds. Something is warmer than when\nyou started.\")
      ((and (< rep-villain 0) (> kills 3))
       \"You have chosen to fight when you could have walked away.\nThat is a kind of person.\")
      ((and (> helps 5) (= kills 0))
       \"You have not raised a hand this whole time. Some players\nnever notice they haven't.\")
      ((> (+ helps kills) 15)
       \"You are moving through the world. Many things have touched you.\")
      (else
       \"You are quiet, mostly. That's alright.\"))))
```

Five hand-crafted patterns. Each recognizes a specific Cortex
signature and returns a specific observation. No AI call. No cost.
Ships in the free tier.

The signal is coarser than a live generation, but the shape is the
same: the game reads what you have done and reflects it. Coarse but
free is often better than fine but paid.

---

## 12.6 A one-question consult

`ask/reasoner` is the cheap, quick verb. Use it when the player asks
the companion a specific question and you want a specific answer.

```scheme
(define (ask-the-companion)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"'What do you want to know?' she says.\")
  (paint-text 20 100 \"[A] am I doing the right thing?\")
  (paint-text 20 130 \"[B] where should I go next?\")
  (paint-text 20 160 \"[C] never mind\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (companion-considers-right-thing))
        ((b) (companion-suggests-next))
        ((c) (skip-question)))))

(define (companion-considers-right-thing)
  (let* ((choices (or (cortex/read 'past-choices) '()))
         (choice-prose (choices->prose choices))
         (answer (ask/reasoner
                   (string-append
                     \"Given a person who did these things: \" choice-prose
                     \". Is there a way to answer their question 'am I doing\n\"
                     \"the right thing?' honestly — not to reassure and not\n\"
                     \"to condemn. One sentence.\"))))
    (paint-text 20 220 (string-append \"'\" answer \"'\"))))
```

The player asks the hardest question. The companion consults a
reasoning model with the full context of what the player has done
and asks for an honest answer — not reassuring, not condemning.
The model returns something like: 'You are doing what you can with
what you know. That is the only honest answer.'

Note the tone-lock in the prompt. Without it the model would tend
toward reassuring platitudes. With it, we get something the player
can sit with.

---

## 12.7 A worked scene: the summary at chapter break

At the end of each chapter, the game offers a chapter-summary the
player can read to feel where they have been.

```scheme
(define (chapter-summary chapter-number)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 (string-append \"~ end of chapter \"
                                   (number->string chapter-number) \" ~\"))
  (paint-text 20 100 \"[A] see what you did this chapter\")
  (paint-text 20 130 \"[B] skip to the next\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (show-chapter-summary chapter-number))
        ((b) (next-chapter))))))

(define (show-chapter-summary chapter-number)
  (let* ((this-chapters-events (cortex-events-in-chapter chapter-number))
         (event-prose (events->prose this-chapters-events))
         (summary (ai/summarize event-prose :style 'narrative-recap)))
    (paint-text 20 40
      (string-append \"Chapter \" (number->string chapter-number) \" — recap:\"))
    (paint-text 20 100 summary)
    (paint-text 20 300 \"[press any key to continue]\")))
```

Cortex has been logging every write. `cortex-events-in-chapter`
filters to just the chapter that just ended. `ai/summarize` renders
those events as a two-line prose recap. The player reads it and
feels the shape of the chapter she just played.

This is the same pattern as 'previously on…' — but for the chapter
she just finished, offered as a reflection rather than a reminder.
Some players will skip it. Some will read every one. Respect both.

---

## 12.8 Common desktop tasks — the shopkeeper's end-of-day reflection

An operator wants a nightly card that summarizes her day: what sold,
what didn't, what conversations happened, what she might want to
think about tomorrow.

```scheme
(define-card 'end-of-day
  :init
  (lambda ()
    (scene/imagine)
    (surface/paper)
    (paint-text 20 40 \"End of the day. Want a two-line summary?\")
    (paint-text 20 100 \"[A] yes   [B] not tonight\")
    (on-key
      (lambda (k)
        (case k
          ((a) (day-summary))
          ((b) (fade-out)))))))

(define (day-summary)
  (let* ((today-events (todays-shop-cortex-entries))
         (event-prose (events->prose today-events))
         (summary (ai/summarize event-prose
                                :style 'shopkeeper-diary
                                :max-sentences 2)))
    (paint-text 20 40 \"Today:\")
    (paint-text 20 100 summary)
    (paint-text 20 300
      \"[A] add a note   [B] archive   [C] pull tomorrow's cart\")))
```

The shopkeeper opts in each evening. The card pulls the day's
Cortex entries — orders, customer messages, promotions — and asks
the reasoner for a two-sentence diary entry. The shopkeeper reads it,
maybe adds a personal note, archives.

This is not a spreadsheet. It is a small daily ritual that gives the
shopkeeper a moment to see her shop as a story rather than a series
of transactions. Over months of use, the diary becomes something she
can look back through when she is having a hard week.

---

## 12.9 Routing patterns

**Once per chapter, tops.** A reflection scene is a spice, not a
staple. If every scene has a reflection, none of them land. Reserve
for chapter breaks, meaningful moments, and player-initiated asks.

**Free fallback for expensive verbs.** Any scene that uses
`afford/deep-think` or `ai/generate` should have a hand-crafted
fallback for players who cannot or will not pay. Detect tier at
runtime; branch on it.

**Companion can be muted.** In the game settings, offer 'quiet
mode.' In quiet mode, companion scenes do not appear. This is a
first-class feature, not a hidden toggle. Some players want no AI in
their story; respect them.

---

## 12.10 Closing

The companion is quiet. She notices. She offers one observation. She
returns to silence. That is the shape.

Do this well and your game has a mirror the player can bring their
choices to. Do it badly and your game has a chatbot the player has
to tolerate.

Chapter 13 adds a third character to the scene — three-way dialogue
with proper blocking. Now that you have single characters, dialogue
trees, and a companion, we scale up to ensemble scenes.")
